            <div type="edition">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>ὁ δῆμος καὶ οἱ πραγματε<supplied reason="lost">υόμενοι Ῥωμαῖοι</supplied>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="imperial"><name type="praenomen" key="Gaius Γαῖος">Γαῖον</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Caesar Καίσαρ">Καίσαρα</name></persName> τὸν τοῦ <persName type="imperial"><name type="cognomen" key="Sebastos Augustus Σεβαστός">Σεβα<supplied reason="lost">στοῦ</supplied></name></persName> <supplied reason="lost">υἱόν, ἡγεμό</supplied>
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/>να τῆς νεότητος, ὕπατο<supplied reason="lost">ν Ἀσίας ἀνέθηκαν</supplied>.
                </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>“The People (of Assos) and the Roman merchants [set this up for] Gaius Caesar, the
                    son of Augustus, Leader of the Youth, consul [of Asia]”</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>Line 1: the nominative forms of demos and “Roman merchants” indicated that they are
                    the active subjects; Bacon et al. restore παρ’ ἡμῖν before Ῥωμαῖοι, thus “the
                    Roman merchants among us”, but Bacon et al. p. 185 ~ IGRR 4.250 ~ Merkelbach no.
                    19 has οἱ πραγματευόμενοι Ῥω[μαῖοι], so this restoration of παρ’ ἡμῖν is
                    unlikely.</p>
                <p>Line 2: the accusative form of C. Caesar and his titles make it clear
                    that he is the direct object and receiving some honor from the aforementioned
                    subjects, despite there being no verb, but the accusative, rather than dative,
                    is a curious choice; Bacon et al. restore καὶ before ἡγεμό=; the IGRR restores
                    πάτρω= instead of ἡγεμό=.</p>
                <p>Line 3: Bacon et al. suggest ὕπατο[ν τῆς Ἀσίας,
                    ἀνέθηκαν] “(for the) consul of Asia, (subjects from line 1) set up (this
                    inscription/statue)”, while Merkelbach thinks ὕπατο[ν ἀποδεδειγμένον]
                    “designated consul” should be restored, both seem reasonable for the context,
                    and the omission of the verb for ‘setting up/erecting’ an inscription or statue
                    is commonly omitted in both Greek and Latin; while very uncommon, a form of
                    ἀνατίθημι and the accusative rather than the usual dative is not unknown, e.g.
                    IG II2 3558: Χολλείδης τὴν ἑαυτοῦ μη[τέρα] | ἀνέθηκαν ἀρετῆς ἕνεκεν | καὶ τῆς
                    πρὸς τὰς θεὰς εὐσεβ[είας]. From the largely secure restoration of the first two
                    lines, there is space for approximately 13-15 letters in the third, I have
                    decided to restore the 13 letter phrase Ἀσίας ἀνέθηκαν, dropping Bacon et al.’s
                    τῆς for spatial reasons. Overall, the lettering is neither excellent nor very
                    poor, but the serifs are more stylized than the letters themselves. 
                    </p> 
                <p>
                    In 5 BCE C. Caesar was appointed princeps iuventutis (here translated into Greek as
                    ἡγεμόνα τῆς νεότητος), “Leader of the Youth”, and consul by Augustus (cf. Suet.
                    Aug. 64; Tac. Ann. 1.3.2), but the latter office was not to be held by him until
                    1 C.E. Leaving for Syria in 1 B.C.E., he assumed the consulship in 1 C.E. (when
                    his name appears in the fasti) while he was in Syria, not arriving in Asia until
                    4 C.E., three years later, shortly before his death. He likely never visited
                    Assos. Merkelbach links this honorific inscription with his nos. 19 and 20,
                    similar dedicatory inscriptions for Livia and Dea Roma, respectively, also set
                    up by the same “People and Roman merchants (of Assos)”. Given the ‘consular’
                    date and Gaius’ death in 4 C.E. the inscription is securely dated from 1 BCE
                    to 4 CE </p></div>
            

